description:
## Goal

Add a loom test that exhaustively verifies the SharedBin retain/release atomic ordering correctness under all possible thread interleavings. The current implementation uses the canonical Arc pattern (Relaxed on retain, Release on release, Acquire fence on final drop) — this ticket converts that claim into a verified property.

## Depends on

fz-q8d.1 (the procbin module is where the test lives; the sync abstraction module slots into the layout chosen in .1).

## Sync abstraction module

New `runtime/src/sync.rs`:

```rust
#[cfg(loom)]
pub use loom::sync::atomic::{AtomicUsize, Ordering, fence};
#[cfg(loom)]
pub use loom::sync::Arc;

#[cfg(not(loom))]
pub use std::sync::atomic::{AtomicUsize, Ordering, fence};
#[cfg(not(loom))]
pub use std::sync::Arc;
```

`SharedBin.refcount` is `crate::sync::AtomicUsize`. `shared_bin_retain` / `shared_bin_release` use `crate::sync::Ordering::*` and `crate::sync::fence`.

## Cargo gating

`runtime/Cargo.toml`:

```toml
[target.'cfg(loom)'.dependencies]
loom = "0.7"
```

Loom is a real dependency, not optional/feature-gated, because the source code references `loom::*` types under `cfg(loom)`. Default builds (no `--cfg loom`) ignore the dependency.

## Loom test

In `runtime/src/procbin.rs` (or a sibling `procbin_loom.rs` if cleaner):

```rust
#[cfg(loom)]
mod loom_tests {
    use super::*;
    use crate::sync::Arc;
    use loom::sync::atomic::AtomicBool;
    use loom::sync::atomic::Ordering::SeqCst;

    /// Two-thread retain/release stress, where main + 2 children each
    /// touch the same SharedBin. Loom enumerates every legal interleaving;
    /// failure modes (UAF, double-free, missed-free) become assertion
    /// failures in the model.
    #[test]
    fn loom_retain_release_two_threads() {
        loom::model(|| {
            // Manual SharedBin construction so the test owns the destructor.
            // Track destructor invocation via an AtomicBool the test can read.
            let destructor_called = Arc::new(AtomicBool::new(false));

            // Heap-allocate the SharedBin with a closure-via-trampoline
            // destructor that flips the flag. We can't pass closures as
            // extern "C" fn directly; use a static trampoline with a
            // thread-local AtomicBool that the test inspects post-run.
            // (Details in the implementation; the loom test does not exercise
            // the standard heap destructor — only the atomic refcount math.)
            let p = build_loom_sharedbin(destructor_called.clone());

            // Initial refcount = 1 (the "main" reference).
            let p_addr = p as usize;

            let t1 = loom::thread::spawn(move || {
                let p = p_addr as *mut SharedBin;
                unsafe { shared_bin_retain(p); }
                unsafe { shared_bin_release(p); }
            });
            let t2 = loom::thread::spawn(move || {
                let p = p_addr as *mut SharedBin;
                unsafe { shared_bin_retain(p); }
                unsafe { shared_bin_release(p); }
            });
            t1.join().unwrap();
            t2.join().unwrap();
            // Final release: should be the last reference and fire the
            // destructor exactly once.
            unsafe { shared_bin_release(p); }
            assert!(destructor_called.load(SeqCst), "destructor must fire on last release");
        });
    }
}
```

The `build_loom_sharedbin` helper constructs a SharedBin without going through `shared_bin_alloc` (which manipulates `LIVE_COUNT` — a runtime gauge loom shouldn't model). The test destructor is a static `extern "C" fn` that flips an atomic, used only in this test binary.

## LIVE_COUNT under cfg(loom)

The heap destructor's `LIVE_COUNT.fetch_sub` is wrapped in `#[cfg(not(loom))]`:

```rust
pub unsafe extern "C" fn shared_bin_destructor_heap(p: *mut SharedBin) {
    let bin = unsafe { Box::from_raw(p) };
    let bytes = unsafe { /* ... */ };
    drop(bytes);
    drop(bin);
    #[cfg(not(loom))]
    LIVE_COUNT.fetch_sub(1, std::sync::atomic::Ordering::Relaxed);
}
```

Loom doesn't model the gauge; production builds do.

## Running

The loom test does not run in default `cargo test`. Invocation:

```bash
RUSTFLAGS="--cfg loom" cargo test --release -p fz-runtime loom_
```

Document in `runtime/README.md` (or a new `RUNNING_LOOM.md`) so anyone touching SharedBin can re-run before commits that change retain/release.

## Acceptance

- The loom test runs under `RUSTFLAGS="--cfg loom"` and passes (no UAF, no double-free, destructor called exactly once across every interleaving).
- Default `cargo test --all` is unaffected — loom is dormant.
- Clippy clean on the sync abstraction and the loom test (under both `cfg(loom)` and `cfg(not(loom))` builds).

## Non-changes

- Production code paths unchanged. The sync abstraction is a re-export, not new logic.
- No CI integration of loom (loom runs are slow and the verification is a one-time correctness witness, not a continuous gate).
